description.narrative: Output 4.4: National and county actors are able to plan, budget, monitor and track expenditures, as well as leverage resources to scale-up evidence-based, innovative and risk-informed approaches to fulfilling children's and adolescents' rights, which contributes to Communication And Advocacy, Cross-Sectoral - Human Rights, Cross-Sectoral - Monitoring, Data And Situation Analyses, Cross-Sectoral - Other Programme Areas, Cross-Sectoral - Social And Behaviour Change, Reducing Child Poverty, Reducing Child Poverty (Covid). UNICEF aims to achieve this through Advocacy And Communications, Advocacy And Public Engagement, Data, Research, Evaluation And Knowledge Management, Evaluations, Research And Data, Fostering Innovation And Use Of New Technologies, Innovation, Systems Strengthening And Institution Building, Systems Strengthening To Leave No One Behind. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: Outcome 4 - Social inclusion: An increased number of children from the poorest & most vulnerable households benefit from shock- responsive & integrated social protection interventions, as well as from child-specific policies

description.narrative: Through UNICEF support, national and county actors have improved capacity and increased resources to sectors that enhance children rights. Budget allocation to social sectors registered a 1.5 per cent;increase from 27 per cent in 2020 to 28.5 per cent;in 2021 at the national level. Counties increased social sector budgets by 0.7 per cent from 41.9 per cent;in 2020 to 42.6 per cent in 2021. UNICEF influenced the drafting of both national and county government post COVID-19 economic recovery strategies and supported the mainstreaming of their priorities in the governments’ plans and budgets. | Status:On-track | As-of Date:24/12/2021
